@article{Burgelman1983a,
	Abstract = {Studies of the relationships between strategy and structure in large, complex firms have produced 2 valid and apparently conflicting propositions regarding the directionality of these relationships - ''structure follows strategy'' and ''strategy follows structure.'' A model was developed to resolve this apparent contradiction by examining the conditions under which each of these propositions may be valid. It is based on 2 critical insights: 1. that the strategic process in such firms consists of the strategic activities of managers from different levels in the organization, and 2. that these strategic activities are either induced by the firm's current concept of corporate strategy, or are autonomous activities that fall outside the scope of the current concept of strategy. The model suggests that large, resource-rich firms are likely to have a reservoir of entrepreneurial potential at operational levels that will express itself in autonomous strategic initiatives. However, at any given time, the bulk of strategic activity in a firm will be of the induced variety. Both of these apparently contradicting propositions can be correct depending on which part of the strategic process is observed.},
