@book{Rumelt1994,
	Abstract = {As an introduction to the book by the same title, the paper outlines the historical evolution of the field of strategic management: the aim of the authors (hereafter RST) is to enable readers to increase the understanding of the challenges strategic management faces today, through an exam of the evolution of the field and a specification of its theoretical antecedents. After briefly sketching the situation of business studies up to the 1960s, RST examine the contributions of the three founding fathers of strategy or strategic management (Chandler, Ansoff and Andrews), and the introduction of new concepts in theory and practice by BCG. The next decade saw the decline of planning and the rise instead of an interest in the link between strategy and performance, as exemplified by the extension of Chandler's work at Harvard, the brewing studies at Purdue and the importing of IO concepts in strategy at Harvard again. The '70s also saw the birth of the process school of strategy, again at Harvard. RST then proceed to analyse the theoretical references of strategy as a field, as well as their recent evolution, always trying to underline the contributions each sub-field has done or has the potential to do. Thus, they focus their attention on economics (and specifically on transaction costs, agency theory and game theory and the new IO), organisational sociology (with the sub-fields of resource-dependency, organisational ecology and new institutionalism) and finally political science (with the interest in voting and political behaviour). This analysis points out that, while the debt strategic management has to all these fields is great, the different interests and approach strategy has still warrant its considerations as a separate field. Finally, RST identify four major questions that should drive the discipline of strategy in the future: How do firms behave? Given that we cannot accept the rationality postulate of economics, what drives the behaviour of the fir